docs.abstract: “Incels” are back in the news after the Toronto attack. They may be a fairly small movement, but they tie into a larger phenomenon.
docs.snippet: “Incels” are back in the news after the Toronto attack. They may be a fairly small movement, but they tie into a larger phenomenon.
docs.lead_paragraph: The recent mass killing in Toronto by a man who once called for an “Incel Rebellion” has drawn attention to an online community of men who lament being “involuntarily celibate” and dream of a social order granting them access to the women of their choice.

headline.main: On Social Media’s Fringes, Growing Extremism Targets Women
headline.print_headline: ‘Incels’ Aren’t Alone In Online Harvesting Of Men’s Sense of Loss

docs.abstract: Galleries and museums are getting creative about presenting work online during the pandemic. Some are open for in-person visits. Here are shows worth viewing either way.
docs.snippet: Galleries and museums are getting creative about presenting work online during the pandemic. Some are open for in-person visits. Here are shows worth viewing either way.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Pull With a Direction,” a lovely and engrossing show at Talwar Gallery, presents a compressed, in-a-nutshell version of the development of Nasreen Mohamedi (1937-1990), one of the most original modernist artists of post-World War II India. While following the trajectory of the much larger retrospective at the Met Breuer in 2016, this show’s 25 works is dominated by the early drawings and some prints of the 1950s and ’60s, when Mohamedi had various styles and materials under consideration. (The years to come are signaled by a handful of photographs, paintings and later abstract drawings.) There’s an alluring wildness to the proceedings, as different artists often emerge from work to work.

headline.main: Three Art Gallery Shows to See Right Now

docs.abstract: While Omar Little on “The Wire” is his best-known role, the actor drew upon his family and neighborhood for a slew of larger-than-life parts.
docs.snippet: While Omar Little on “The Wire” is his best-known role, the actor drew upon his family and neighborhood for a slew of larger-than-life parts.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a memorable scene in HBO’s “Lovecraft Country,” a sullen, swollen-eyed Montrose Freeman stands alone in a crowded underground ballroom as his lover, Sammy, in drag, beckons him to the dance floor. Wearing a red silk shirt, Montrose, played by Michael K. Williams, glistens as his character, a queer Black man, struggles with his sexuality and his race in 1950s Chicago.

headline.main: Michael K. Williams Brought His Whole Life to His Characters
headline.print_headline: An Actor Who Brought  His Whole Life to His Roles

docs.abstract: Mr. Soros’s group will invest $150 million in grants for Black-led racial justice groups, and another $70 million toward local grants for criminal justice reform and civic engagement opportunities.
docs.snippet: Mr. Soros’s group will invest $150 million in grants for Black-led racial justice groups, and another $70 million toward local grants for criminal justice reform and civic engagement opportunities.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Open Society Foundations, the philanthropic group founded by the business magnate George Soros, announced on Monday that it was investing $220 million in efforts to achieve racial equality in America, a huge financial undertaking that will support several Black-led racial justice groups for years to come.

headline.main: George Soros’s Foundation Pours $220 Million Into Racial Equality Push
headline.print_headline: Soros Invests $220 Million To Help Realize Racial Equality

docs.abstract: The police seize and kill young men in Nigeria. Then pastors, lawyers and so-called human rights advocates squeeze money out of their families, promising to help find them.
docs.snippet: The police seize and kill young men in Nigeria. Then pastors, lawyers and so-called human rights advocates squeeze money out of their families, promising to help find them.
docs.lead_paragraph: AWKA, Nigeria — In the small family portrait gallery hanging above the television in the cozy home of the Iloanya family, only two framed photographs remain that include the youngest son, Chijioke.

headline.main: Police Took Their Son Away. Then the Merchants of Hope Showed Up.

docs.abstract: He was never afraid to speak plainly about injustice or to stand up for marginalized people.
docs.snippet: He was never afraid to speak plainly about injustice or to stand up for marginalized people.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Anthony Bourdain visited the San Francisco Bay Area in 2015 for his CNN show “Anthony Bourdain:Parts Unknown,” he made a point of sitting down for a meal with one of the founders of the Black Panther Party, Bobby Seale. And he didn’t just talk about the food. He provided viewers an astute history of the group, its important role in the black freedom movement and the African-American community, and its suppression by the government.

headline.main: Anthony Bourdain Was the Kind of ‘Bad Boy’ We Need More Of
headline.print_headline: The Kind of ‘Bad Boy’ We Needed

docs.abstract: U.S. officials said the two days of discussions would continue, but accused the Chinese delegation of violating the format for meetings that had sought to find common ground between the superpowers.
docs.snippet: U.S. officials said the two days of discussions would continue, but accused the Chinese delegation of violating the format for meetings that had sought to find common ground between the superpowers.
docs.lead_paragraph: ANCHORAGE — Even before the Biden administration’s first face-to-face meeting with senior Chinese diplomats on Thursday, American officials predicted the discussions would not go well. They were right: The traditional few minutes of opening greetings and remarks dissolved into more than an hour of very public verbal jousting, confirming the expected confrontational tone between the geopolitical rivals.

headline.main: In First Talks, Dueling Accusations Set Testy Tone for U.S.-China Diplomacy
headline.print_headline: In First Talks, Dueling Accusations Set Testy Tone for U.S.-China Diplomacy

docs.abstract: The image of Jen Reid, fist clenched atop the plinth in the English city where Edward Colston once stood, became a symbol of protest online. Now, it’s there in resin and steel.
docs.snippet: The image of Jen Reid, fist clenched atop the plinth in the English city where Edward Colston once stood, became a symbol of protest online. Now, it’s there in resin and steel.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Jen Reid had never marched in a Black Lives Matter protest before she took to the streets of Bristol, England, on June 7. By the end of that angry day, she had clambered up to stand in the place of a 17th-century slave trader, whose bronze statue had been pulled down and dumped in the city’s harbor.

headline.main: Statue of Black Protester Is Raised in Place of Bristol Slave Trader
headline.print_headline: Where British Slave Trader’s Statue Stood, Black Protester’s Image Rises
